  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.3345" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <opener>Dear D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi> Schuchardt, </opener>

        <p>I shall leave San Sebastian on Monday and arrive at Collegio do Senhor da Boa Fortuna, Vizeu, Beira Alta, Portugal, on the 12<hi
            rendition="#sup">th</hi> of September. You had better address your publications thither. I expect to pass the 10<hi
            rendition="#sup">th</hi> at Salamanca, and shall call for letters there. I sent off my case of books from here this morning to the Douane at Villar Formoso. They make it weigh here 90 kilos, though at Paris at Hendaye and at Irun they labelled it 90. I dont think any books have been abstracted, though, perhaps owing to the shaking in the train, a certain space has been formed at the top layer. In the hymn to S<hi
            rendition="#sup">t</hi> Ignatio in <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">La Union Vascongada</hi> no 708 what is <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">errepiretan</hi>
          </foreign>? A waiter here says it is <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">romeria</hi> but another person says that this word is <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
erretireta</hi>
          </foreign> – perhaps from <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
retraite</hi>. <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">Kgeinuz</hi> I take to be for <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">keignuz</hi> = keiñuz</foreign> = beckoning. I still repeat that I believed <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">deitzen</hi>
          </foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
deritzen</hi>
          </foreign> to be the same word, but quite distinct from <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">eritzen</hi>

          </foreign>, though some of the forms of the two verbs coincide, as is the case in other languages. I thought that you had muddled them up. I feel insulted, I must say, when on saying to a Basque peasant <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">agur</hi> he replies <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">adios</hi>, or if I say <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">gabon</hi> and he replies <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">
igualmente</hi>: but there is no doubt that Basque is in its death-throes. I think I have seen in print <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">é</hi> for <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">ere</hi>. I heard it in the mouth of a man who lives at Loyola a hamlet half way between <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.119">Donostia</ref> and Astigarraga. I walked to the latter place a few days ago. They speak very good <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Basque</ref> there. I was surprised at some women saying to me, when I asked what tree they called astigarra, not eztaki<hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">t</hi> but <foreign xml:lang="eu">
eztaki<hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">n</hi>
          </foreign>. I found something like this in S<hi
            rendition="#sup">t</hi> Hélène if I remember right. Can the word <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
deitzen</hi>
          </foreign>
          <note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">V. OEH, s.v. <foreign xml:lang="eu">
              <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
jeitzi</hi>
            </foreign>.</note> = traire, to milk come from the word which is <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">teat</hi> in English, or can it be related to the difficult word <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">dairy</hi> in English? <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">Notes and Queries</hi> of August 12<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi> published my letter about Queen Elizabeths Ghost, with a quotation from Uriartes month of Mary in Biscayan. My money crisis is over.</p>
        <closer>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1402">E. S. Dodgson</persName>. </signed>
          <dateline>
            <note n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">Datum am rechten Rand.</note> 25 August, 1893.</dateline>
        </closer>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
      </div>
